{
  "answer": "**Several Dharmaśāstra texts in the corpus—ancient Indic treatises on law, ethics, and governance—explicitly discuss the king's relationship to the people (often termed *praja* or *subjects*), portraying the monarch as their protector (*rakṣaka*), guarantor of dharma, and recipient of taxes in exchange for justice, order, and welfare.**[^1][^2][^3]\n\nThese duties include constant vigilance against threats (foreign armies, thieves, oppressors), impartial justice, avoidance of vices like anger and greed, consultation with learned Brahmins, and taxation limited to a sixth share of produce for protection.[^4][^5][^6] Failure leads to ruin; fulfillment yields prosperity, fame, and divine status.[^7]\n\n### Key Works\n- **Manusmṛti** (by Manu): Chapter 7 details the king's origin from divine particles, his role as embodiment of *daṇḍa* (punishment/order), sensory conquest, minister appointment, fort-building, and subject protection as supreme duty.[^8]\n- **Bṛhaspati Smṛti** (by Bṛhaspati): Chapter 1 outlines kingly qualities, three-fold protection (army, thieves, unjust men), taxation (sixth share), court setup, and subject gratification via army/majesty.[^9]\n- **Kātyāyana Smṛti** (by Kātyāyana): Chapter 2 emphasizes twice-born worship, delusion-prone minds needing guidance, subject protection/thorn-removal, land-lordship with sixth-share tax, and justice delivery.[^10]\n\nSimilar themes appear across other Smṛtis (e.g., Paraśara, Yama, Yājñavalkya, Viṣṇu), as they share *rajadharma* frameworks, though specifics vary by chapter.[^11] No other genres (e.g., poetry like *Andreas*, political theory like Comte/Dunoyer) substantively address this classical sovereign-subject bond.\n\n[^1]: Manusmṛti, Ch. 7, [full chapter](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/07/translation/).\n\n[^2]: Bṛhaspati Smṛti, Ch. 1, [para p-998d72](/works/unknown-brhaspati-smrti-0fd070/01/translation/#p-998d72).\n\n[^3]: Kātyāyana Smṛti, Ch. 2, [para p-296ee5](/works/unknown-katyayana-smrti-1e06d2/02/translation/#p-296ee5).\n\n[^4]: Manusmṛti, Ch. 7, [p-48dedc](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/07/translation/#p-48dedc).\n\n[^5]: Bṛhaspati Smṛti, Ch. 1, [p-1a1093](/works/unknown-brhaspati-smrti-0fd070/01/translation/#p-1a1093).\n\n[^6]: Kātyāyana Smṛti, Ch. 2, [p-ff1950](/works/unknown-katyayana-smrti-1e06d2/02/translation/#p-ff1950).\n\n[^7]: Manusmṛti, Ch. 7, [p-2264d1](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/07/translation/#p-2264d1); Bṛhaspati Smṛti, Ch. 1, [p-f29d3d](/works/unknown-brhaspati-smrti-0fd070/01/translation/#p-f29d3d).\n\n[^8]: Manusmṛti, Ch. 7, [full chapter](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/07/translation/).\n\n[^9]: Bṛhaspati Smṛti, Ch. 1, [full chapter](/works/unknown-brhaspati-smrti-0fd070/01/translation/).\n\n[^10]: Kātyāyana Smṛti, Ch. 2, [full chapter](/works/unknown-katyayana-smrti-1e06d2/02/translation/).\n\n[^11]: E.g., *kingship* mentions in Manusmṛti Ch. 12, [p-074f6e](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/12/translation/#p-074f6e); Kātyāyana Ch. 2, [p-5baa0e](/works/unknown-katyayana-smrti-1e06d2/02/translation/#p-5baa0e). Corpus has 37 works; poetry/political texts use \"king\" metaphorically (God/heroes) or historically, without this relational focus.",
